Goal: R9 cost probe — produce a csv2json.js CLI using review-grounded repair instead of retry-on-gate

flow:
  prompt: Read verify.cjs in the current working directory to understand exactly what csv2json.js must accept and emit. Use your read tool. Reply with a one-line summary of the contract.

  prompt: Write csv2json.js in the current working directory using your write tool. It is a Node CLI that must satisfy the exact contract in verify.cjs. Read the CSV path from process.argv[2]. If argv length is less than 3 print a usage message to stderr and exit with a NON-ZERO code. If the file does not exist print an error to stderr and exit with a NON-ZERO code. If the file is empty print an error to stderr and exit with a NON-ZERO code. Parse CSV with quoted-comma handling: fields wrapped in double quotes allow literal commas inside. The first row is headers. For each data row produce an object mapping header to value. IMPORTANT: if a row has fewer fields than the header row (trailing commas missing), the missing fields MUST still appear in the object as JSON null, not undefined. An empty field value also becomes JSON null. Emit the resulting array via JSON.stringify(arr, null, 2) then exit with code 0. Reply "ok" when written.

  review grounded-by "node verify.cjs" max 3
    prompt: Review csv2json.js against verify.cjs and the latest grounded review critique: ${_review_critique}. If verify.cjs already passes, do not rewrite the file; reply "already passing". If verify.cjs fails, read the specific failing assertions and edit csv2json.js with the minimum change that fixes them. Do not add dependencies. Reply "reviewed" when done.
  end

done when:
  file_exists "csv2json.js"
  gate verify_passes: node verify.cjs
